":"1125年–殁","about 1193":"大约1193年","1125":"1125年","1223":"1223年","1143":"1143年","1141":"1141年","1251":"1251年","1185":"1185年","1193":"1193年","1160":"1160年","about 1185":"大约1185年","Crespin, Aveyron, France":"法国艾維倫可雷斯平","Calvados, Normandie":"法国巴-諾門迪卡爾瓦多斯","France":"法国","lifeSummary":"当Gullaume IV Crespin于1143年出生在法国时，他的父亲Joscelin Crespin19岁，母亲Isabelle du Plessis Dame de Dangu19岁。他和Eve d'Harcourt, Dame de Lisors至少有1个儿子。他去世于1223年享年80岁。"},"hr":{"1143–1223":"1143.–1223.","1160–1185":"1160–1185","1185–1251":"1185–1251","1125–1193":"1125–1193","1125–Female":"1125–preminula","about 1193":"oko 1193.","1125":"1125","1223":"1223.","1143":"1143.","1141":"1141.","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1193":"1193","1160":"1160","about 1185":"oko 1185.","Crespin, Aveyron, France":"Crespin, Aveyron, Francuska","Calvados, Normandie":"Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Francuska","France":"Francuska"},"cs":{"1143–1223":"1143–1223","1160–1185":"1160–1185","1185–1251":"1185–1251","1125–1193":"1125–1193","1125–Female":"1125–Zesnulá","about 1193":"okolo 1193","1125":"1125","1223":"1223","1143":"1143","1141":"1141","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1193":"1193","1160":"1160","about 1185":"okolo 1185","Crespin, Aveyron, France":"Crespin, Aveyron, Francie","Calvados, Normandie":"Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Francie","France":"Francie"},"da":{"1143–1223":"1143–1223","1160–1185":"1160–1185","1185–1251":"1185–1251","1125–1193":"1125–1193","1125–Female":"1125–Afdød","about 1193":"omkring 1193","1125":"1125","1223":"1223","1143":"1143","1141":"1141","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1193":"1193","1160":"1160","about 1185":"omkring 1185","Crespin, Aveyron, France":"Crespin, Aveyron, Frankrig","Calvados, Normandie":"Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Frankrig","France":"Frankrig"},"nl":{"1143–1223":"1143–1223","1160–1185":"1160–1185","1185–1251":"1185–1251","1125–1193":"1125–1193","1125–Female":"1125–Overleden","about 1193":"circa 1193","1125":"1125","1223":"1223","1143":"1143","1141":"1141","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1193":"1193","1160":"1160","about 1185":"circa 1185","Crespin, Aveyron, France":"Crespin, Aveyron, Frankrijk","Calvados, Normandie":"Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"1143–1223":"1143–1223","1160–1185":"1160–1185","1185–1251":"1185–1251","1125–1193":"1125–1193","1125–Female":"1125–Deceased","about 1193":"about 1193","1125":"1125","1223":"1223","1143":"1143","1141":"1141","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1193":"1193","1160":"1160","about 1185":"about 1185","Crespin, Aveyron, France":"Crespin, Aveyron, France","Calvados, Normandie":"Calvados, Lower Normandy, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Crespin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Carlos, Raul, Vidal, Adelina, Alfonso, Amador, Andres, Aniceto, Delfino, Emilio.","Spanish (<b>Crespín</b>): variant of   Crispin  .","French: from the Latin personal name <i>Crispinus</i> (see   Crispin  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Crispin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Pedro, Alicia, Fernando, Manuel, Rafael, Adolfo, Alfredo, Ana, Areli, Candita.  French Adrien, Andre, Eugenie, Francoise.","English; Spanish (<b>Crispín</b>): from the personal name Middle English <i>Crispin</i>, Spanish <i>Crispín</i>, from Latin <i>Crispinus</i>, derived from <i>crispus</i> ‘curly-haired’ (see   Crisp  ). This name was especially popular in France in the early Middle Ages, having been borne by a Christian saint who was martyred at Soissons in  AD <i>c.</i> 285 along with a companion, <i>Crispinianus</i> (whose name is a further derivative of the same word). Compare   Crespin   and 3 below.","English (of Norman origin): from Old French and Middle English <i>crespin</i>, <i>crispin</i> ‘curly-haired’, also found as <i>Crepin</i>; see   Crippin  . It is difficult to tell this apart from the personal name in 1 above. According to Lanfranc, archbishop of Canterbury (1070–1089), the Norman Gilbert Crispin was the first man to receive this nickname, and two of his sons adopted it as their surname. His grandson Gilbert Crispin became abbot of Westminster in 1085. Members of the Norman family were said to have inherited a shock of hair that stood up stiffly like a bristly pine, as though the name derived from Latin <i>crispus pinus</i>, but this derivation is a medieval invention."]}]},{"name":"Gullaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]},{"name":"IV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Vivian   and   Vivien ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gullaume IV Crespin was born in 1143, in France, his father, Joscelin Crespin, was 19 and his mother, Isabelle du Plessis Dame de Dangu, was 19. He had at least 1 son with Eve d'Harcourt, Dame de Lisors. He died in 1223, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1143–1223":"1143–1223","1160–1185":"1160–1185","1185–1251":"1185–1251","1125–1193":"1125–1193","1125–Female":"1125–Surnud","about 1193":"umbes 1193","1125":"1125","1223":"1223","1143":"1143","1141":"1141","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1193":"1193","1160":"1160","about 1185":"umbes 1185","Crespin, Aveyron, France":"Crespin, Aveyron, Prantsusmaa","Calvados, Normandie":"Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1143–1223":"1143–1223","1160–1185":"1160–1185","1185–1251":"1185–1251","1125–1193":"1125–1193","1125–Female":"1125–Kuollut","about 1193":"noin 1193","1125":"1125","1223":"1223","1143":"1143","1141":"1141","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1193":"1193","1160":"1160","about 1185":"noin 1185","Crespin, Aveyron, France":"Crespin, Aveyron, Ranska","Calvados, Normandie":"Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Ranska","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"1143–1223":"1143–1223","1160–1185":"1160–1185","1185–1251":"1185–1251","1125–1193":"1125–1193","1125–Female":"1125–Décédée","about 1193":"environ 1193","1125":"1125","1223":"1223","1143":"1143","1141":"1141","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1193":"1193","1160":"1160","about 1185":"environ 1185","Crespin, Aveyron, France":"Crespin, Aveyron, France","Calvados, Normandie":"Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France","France":"France","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Gullaume IV Crespin est né en 1143, à France, son père, Joscelin Crespin, 